(40, 12, 20, 42, 4, 18, 18, 'bruised', 'Connection of Healing and Restoration', 'Both passages emphasize the care for the bruised and brokenhearted. Matthew speaks of not breaking a bruised reed, while Luke mentions healing those that are bruised.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 12, 20, 19, 147, 3, 3, 'bruised reed shall he not break', 'Healing the Brokenhearted', 'This connection highlights the theme of healing and restoration found in both passages. Matthew 12:20 speaks of not breaking a bruised reed, while Psalms 147:3 mentions healing the broken in heart, emphasizing compassion for the vulnerable.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 12, 20, 25, 3, 31, 34, 'a bruised reed shall he not break', 'Compassion and Mercy in Affliction', 'Both passages emphasize God''s compassion and care for the vulnerable. Matthew highlights the gentle treatment of the bruised and weak, while Lamentations assures that God does not willingly afflict His people, showing His mercy even in grief.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 12, 20, 19, 51, 17, 17, 'a bruised reed shall he not break', 'Connection of Brokenness and Care', 'This connection highlights the theme of Gods compassion towards those who are broken or bruised. Both passages emphasize that God values a broken spirit and will not despise those who are in a state of need or weakness.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 12, 21, 23, 11, 10, 10, NULL, 'Connection of Gentiles Seeking', 'Both passages emphasize the role of the Gentiles in seeking trust and rest in the figure associated with Jesse. The phrase ''the Gentiles'' appears in both, linking their hope and search for salvation.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 12, 21, 45, 15, 12, 13, NULL, 'Connection of Gentile Trust', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of Gentiles placing their trust in the figure associated with Jesse. This connection highlights the continuity of hope and faith among Gentiles in the context of salvation.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 12, 21, 23, 42, 4, 4, 'the Gentiles trust', 'Gentiles and Judgment Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of the Gentiles'' trust in the figure described in Isaiah, who is committed to establishing justice. Both passages emphasize the broader reach of his influence, extending to the isles and the Gentiles.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 12, 21, 51, 1, 27, 27, 'the Gentiles trust', 'Connection of Gentiles and Christ', 'Both passages emphasize the role of Gentiles in relation to Christ. Matthew highlights the trust of the Gentiles in His name, while Colossians reveals the mystery of Christ among the Gentiles, indicating their inclusion in the hope of glory.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 12, 21, 49, 1, 12, 13, 'the Gentiles trust', 'Trust of the Gentiles', 'This connection highlights the theme of trust in Christ, as both passages emphasize the Gentiles'' faith and those who first trusted in Him. The mention of the Gentiles in Matthew aligns with the call for all to believe in Ephesians.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 12, 22, 42, 11, 14, 15, 'dumb: and he healed him', 'Healing of the Dumb Possessed', 'Both passages emphasize the healing of a dumb person possessed by a devil. They describe the miraculous act of casting out the devil, resulting in the individual speaking, which astonishes the onlookers.', 'parallel', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 12, 22, 23, 29, 18, 18, 'the blind and dumb both spake and saw', 'Healing of the Blind and Deaf', 'Both passages emphasize the healing of the blind and deaf. Matthew describes a specific healing, while Isaiah prophesies a future time when the deaf will hear and the blind will see.', 'prophecy', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 12, 22, 41, 7, 35, 37, NULL, 'Healing of the Mute and Deaf', 'Both passages emphasize the miraculous healing of individuals who are unable to speak or hear. The phrase ''dumb to speak'' in Matthew parallels the healing of the ''dumb'' in Mark, showcasing Jesus'' authority over physical ailments.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 12, 22, 23, 35, 5, 6, 'the blind and dumb', 'Healing of the Blind and Dumb', 'Both passages emphasize the healing of the blind and the dumb. Matthew 12:22 describes a specific healing, while Isaiah 35:5-6 prophesies that the eyes of the blind shall be opened and the tongue of the dumb shall sing.', 'prophecy', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 12, 22, 41, 3, 11, 11, NULL, 'Healing and Recognition of Authority', 'Both passages emphasize the recognition of Jesus'' authority over unclean spirits. In Matthew, the healing of the possessed man demonstrates His power, while in Mark, the unclean spirits acknowledge Him as the Son of God.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 12, 22, 44, 26, 18, 18, 'blind and dumb', 'Healing and Spiritual Enlightenment', 'This connection highlights the theme of healing and restoration from blindness and darkness. Both passages emphasize the transformation from a state of affliction to one of clarity and light.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 12, 22, 40, 4, 24, 24, NULL, 'Healing of the Possessed', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus healing those possessed with devils. Matthew 12:22 specifically mentions a possessed individual who was healed, while Matthew 4:24 refers to many who were possessed and healed by Him.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 12, 23, 40, 9, 27, 27, 'Son of David', 'Connection of ''Son of David''', 'Both passages emphasize the title ''Son of David'' as a recognition of Jesus'' identity. The amazement of the crowd in Matthew 12:23 and the plea of the blind men in Matthew 9:27 highlight the significance of this title in acknowledging Jesus'' messianic role.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 12, 23, 40, 22, 42, 43, 'the son of David', 'Connection of David''s Son', 'Both passages emphasize the identity of Christ as the ''Son of David.'' This connection highlights the recognition of Jesus'' lineage and authority in relation to David.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 12, 23, 43, 4, 29, 29, 'Is not this the son of David?', 'Recognition of Jesus'' Identity', 'Both passages emphasize the recognition of Jesus as the Messiah. In Matthew, the people question if He is ''the son of David,'' while in John, the woman identifies Him as ''the Christ.'' This connection highlights the acknowledgment of Jesus'' messianic role.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 12, 23, 40, 15, 30, 31, 'Is not this the son of David?', 'Recognition of Jesus'' Authority', 'This connection highlights the amazement of the crowds in both passages. In Matthew 12:23, the people recognize Jesus as ''the son of David,'' while in Matthew 15:30-31, they glorify God after witnessing His miraculous healings, indicating their acknowledgment of His divine authority.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 12, 23, 40, 21, 9, 9, 'Son of David', 'Recognition of Jesus as Messiah', 'Both passages emphasize the recognition of Jesus as the ''Son of David,'' highlighting the people''s acknowledgment of his messianic identity. This connection illustrates a consistent theme of Jesus being linked to the Davidic lineage.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 12, 23, 43, 7, 40, 42, 'son of David', 'Connection of Davidic Lineage', 'Both passages emphasize the identity of Jesus as linked to David. Matthew highlights the amazement of the people recognizing Him as ''the son of David,'' while John discusses the expectation of the Messiah coming from David''s lineage, specifically from Bethlehem.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 12, 24, 41, 3, 22, 22, 'by Beelzebub the prince of the devils', 'Accusation of Beelzebub', 'Both passages emphasize the accusation that Jesus casts out demons by Beelzebub, linking the two accounts of opposition against Him. This connection highlights the consistent challenge Jesus faced from religious leaders regarding His authority.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
