(40, 19, 26, 24, 32, 17, 17, 'with God all things are possible', 'Divine Power and Possibility', 'Both passages emphasize that with God, nothing is impossible. They highlight God''s omnipotence in creating and accomplishing what seems unattainable to humans.', 'theme', 0.7969999999999999, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 19, 26, 1, 18, 14, 14, 'with God all things are possible', 'Possibility with God', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of God''s ability to accomplish what seems impossible for humans. In Matthew, Jesus states that ''with God all things are possible,'' while in Genesis, the question ''Is any thing too hard for the Lord?'' underscores God''s power to fulfill His promises.', 'theme', 0.727, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 19, 27, 50, 3, 8, 8, 'forsaken all, and followed thee', 'Loss for Christ''s Gain', 'This connection highlights the theme of forsaking all for the sake of Christ. Both passages emphasize the value of losing worldly possessions in pursuit of a deeper relationship with Jesus.', 'theme', 0.40499999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 19, 27, 42, 18, 28, 28, NULL, 'Peter''s Declaration of Sacrifice', 'Both passages emphasize Peter''s acknowledgment of leaving everything to follow Jesus. This connection highlights the theme of sacrifice and commitment in discipleship.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 19, 27, 42, 5, 11, 11, 'forsaken all, and followed thee', 'Forsaking All to Follow Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the act of forsaking all to follow Jesus. Peter''s question in Matthew reflects the commitment shown by the fishermen in Luke, who also ''forsook all'' to become his disciples.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 19, 27, 41, 1, 17, 20, 'forsaken all', 'Forsaking All to Follow Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of forsaking one''s former life to follow Jesus. In Matthew, Peter mentions having ''forsaken all,'' while in Mark, the disciples ''forsook their nets'' to become followers.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 19, 27, 5, 33, 9, 9, 'forsaken all, and followed thee', 'Forsaking Family for Covenant', 'This connection highlights the theme of forsaking familial ties for the sake of following God''s commands. Both passages emphasize the commitment to God''s word over earthly relationships.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 19, 27, 40, 4, 20, 22, 'forsaken all', 'Disciples'' Immediate Response', 'Both passages emphasize the immediate commitment of the disciples to follow Jesus. In Matthew 4:20-22, they leave their nets and family, paralleling Peter''s declaration of having forsaken all in Matthew 19:27.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 19, 27, 40, 9, 9, 9, 'followed thee', 'Following Jesus and Sacrifice', 'This connection highlights the theme of following Jesus and the sacrifices made by His disciples. In both passages, the act of following Jesus is central, with Peter referencing their forsaking of all to follow Him, while Matthew responds to Jesus'' call to follow Him.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 19, 28, 42, 22, 28, 30, 'judging the twelve tribes of Israel', 'Judgment and Thrones Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the promise of the disciples sitting on thrones and judging the twelve tribes of Israel. This connection highlights the shared theme of reward for faithfulness in following Jesus.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 19, 28, 40, 25, 31, 31, 'throne of his glory', 'Connection of Glory and Judgment', 'Both passages emphasize the ''throne of his glory'' and the role of Jesus in judgment. In Matthew 19:28, the promise of sitting on thrones is linked to the regeneration when Jesus judges, which is echoed in Matthew 25:31 when he comes in glory to judge.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 19, 28, 46, 6, 2, 3, 'judging the twelve tribes of Israel', 'Judgment by the Saints', 'This connection highlights the theme of judgment, as both passages discuss the role of followers of Christ in judging. Matthew 19:28 mentions the disciples judging the twelve tribes of Israel, while 1 Corinthians 6:2-3 states that the saints shall judge the world and angels.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 19, 28, 66, 20, 4, 4, 'judging the twelve tribes of Israel', 'Judgment and Thrones Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of thrones and judgment. In Matthew, Jesus promises his followers thrones for judging Israel, while Revelation depicts thrones where judgment is given to those who remained faithful.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 19, 28, 23, 65, 17, 17, 'regeneration', 'New Creation and Regeneration', 'This connection highlights the theme of regeneration and new creation. Matthew speaks of a future time of judgment and glory, while Isaiah proclaims the creation of new heavens and a new earth.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 19, 28, 23, 66, 22, 22, 'regeneration when the Son of man', 'Judgment and New Creation', 'This connection highlights the theme of regeneration and the establishment of a new order. Both passages emphasize the permanence of God''s creation and the role of His followers in a renewed context.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 19, 28, 40, 16, 27, 27, 'shall sit upon twelve thrones', 'Connection of Reward and Judgment', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of reward for followers of Jesus. In Matthew 19:28, the promise of sitting on thrones relates to the judgment mentioned in Matthew 16:27, where rewards are given according to works.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 19, 29, 42, 18, 29, 30, 'for my names sake', 'Rewards for Sacrifice', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of sacrifice for the sake of God and the promise of receiving manifold rewards in return, both in this life and the next. They highlight the idea that leaving behind family and possessions for God''s kingdom leads to abundant blessings.', 'theme', 1.0, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 19, 29, 41, 10, 29, 30, 'for my names sake', 'Connection of Sacrifice and Reward', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of forsaking familial and material ties for Jesus'' sake, promising a hundredfold reward and eternal life. The parallel structure in both verses highlights the sacrifices made and the blessings received in return.', 'theme', 0.8879999999999999, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 19, 29, 50, 3, 8, 8, 'forsaken houses, or brethren, or sisters', 'Loss for Christ''s Sake', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of forsaking worldly attachments for the sake of Christ. Matthew speaks of forsaking family and lands, while Philippians highlights counting all things as loss to gain Christ.', 'theme', 0.804, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 19, 29, 42, 14, 26, 26, 'for my names sake', 'Discipleship and Sacrifice', 'Both passages emphasize the cost of discipleship, highlighting the necessity of forsaking familial ties for the sake of following Jesus. They illustrate the theme of prioritizing commitment to Christ over earthly relationships.', 'theme', 0.72, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 19, 29, 40, 16, 25, 25, NULL, 'Sacrifice for Eternal Reward', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of losing one''s life or possessions for the sake of Jesus, leading to a greater reward. They highlight the paradox of sacrifice resulting in eternal life and abundant blessings.', 'theme', 0.692, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 19, 29, 40, 10, 37, 38, 'forsaken houses, or brethren, or sisters', 'Sacrifice for Christ''s Sake', 'Both passages emphasize the necessity of prioritizing Jesus over familial ties. They highlight the theme of forsaking relationships and personal sacrifice for the sake of following Him.', 'theme', 0.643, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 19, 29, 60, 4, 14, 14, 'for my names sake', 'Reproach for Christ''s Name', 'Both passages emphasize the sacrifices made for Christ''s name and the resulting blessings. Matthew highlights the rewards for forsaking family and possessions, while 1 Peter speaks of happiness in being reproached for Christ''s name.', 'theme', 0.573, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 19, 30, 40, 20, 16, 16, NULL, 'First and Last Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the reversal of status, stating that ''the first shall be last'' and ''the last shall be first.'' This connection highlights a theme of humility and divine selection.', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 19, 30, 42, 13, 30, 30, 'first shall be last; and the last shall be first', 'First and Last Concept', 'Both passages emphasize the reversal of status, where those considered last will become first and vice versa. This thematic parallel highlights the idea of unexpected outcomes in the kingdom of God.', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 19, 30, 41, 10, 31, 31, 'the last shall be first', 'Connection of Last and First', 'Both passages emphasize the reversal of status, stating that ''the last shall be first'' and ''the first shall be last.'' This connection highlights a shared theme of humility and the unexpected nature of God''s kingdom.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 19, 30, 40, 21, 31, 32, NULL, 'First and Last Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the reversal of expectations regarding who enters the kingdom of God. In Matthew 19:30, the idea that ''the first shall be last'' connects to Matthew 21:31-32, where those considered last, like publicans and harlots, enter before the religious leaders.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 19, 30, 42, 18, 13, 14, 'the last shall be first', 'Humility and Exaltation Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the reversal of status based on humility and pride. Matthew highlights that the last shall be first, while Luke illustrates that the humble publican is justified over the self-exalting Pharisee.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 19, 30, 45, 5, 20, 21, NULL, 'Grace and Reversal of Status', 'Both passages emphasize a reversal of status, where those who seem first may ultimately be last, and where sin''s abundance leads to an even greater abundance of grace. This connection highlights the transformative power of grace in contrast to human expectations.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 19, 30, 45, 9, 30, 33, 'the last shall be first', 'Righteousness and Reversal of Status', 'Both passages emphasize a reversal of status, where those who seem last, like the Gentiles, attain righteousness through faith, while those who are first, like Israel, fail due to reliance on works. This connection highlights the unexpected nature of God''s grace.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
