(40, 20, 6, 20, 19, 15, 15, 'standing idle', 'Connection of Idleness and Consequences', 'This connection highlights the theme of idleness and its consequences. Both passages emphasize the negative outcomes of being idle, with Matthew questioning why individuals are ''standing idle'' and Proverbs warning that an ''idle soul shall suffer hunger.''', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 20, 6, 21, 9, 10, 10, 'standing idle', 'Work and Urgency in Life', 'This connection highlights the theme of urgency in labor and the importance of making the most of one''s time. Both passages emphasize the necessity of action and diligence while one is still alive.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 20, 6, 26, 16, 49, 49, 'standing idle', 'Idleness and Responsibility', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of idleness and its consequences. In Matthew, the question of idleness is posed directly, while Ezekiel condemns the abundance of idleness in Sodom, linking it to neglect of the poor.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 20, 6, 42, 23, 40, 43, 'standing idle', 'Idle and Redemption', 'This connection highlights the theme of being called at the last moment. Both passages emphasize the idea of individuals being invited to participate in God''s plan, whether standing idle or seeking redemption.', 'theme', 0.307, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 20, 7, 49, 2, 11, 12, 'whatsoever is right, that shall ye receive', 'Inclusion of the Unhired Workers', 'This connection highlights the theme of inclusion and hope for those who are marginalized or excluded. In Matthew, the workers who were not hired represent those without a place, while Ephesians speaks of Gentiles who were once without Christ and hope, emphasizing God''s invitation to all.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
